'''Amir Reko''' (born 1963), known by his ''[[nom de guerre]]'' '''Makedonac''' ("the Macedonian"), is a [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian]]-[[Denmark|Danish]] entrepreneur, formerly military officer in the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] (JNA), and a commander in the [[Army of the Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (ARBiH) during the [[Bosnian War]] (1992–1995).

An ethnic [[Bosniak]], Reko was born in the hamlet of Gudelj of the village [[Jošanica, Foča|Jošanica]] in [[Foča]] in eastern Bosnia.{{sfn|Ličnosti}} During [[World War II in Yugoslavia|World War II]] his grandmother was saved by a [[Serbs|Serb]].{{sfn|DW 2017}} He finished primary school in the village of [[Ustikolina]], after which he moved to [[Sarajevo]] on higher studies, finishing middle technical school in 1982.{{sfn|Ličnosti}} He finished the Army military school in 1986 as an infantry.{{sfn|Ličnosti}} He served as an officer (''časnik'') in [[Novo Mesto]] (in Slovenia), [[Gospić]] (Croatia), [[Pljevlja]] (Montenegro), [[Bitola]] (Macedonia), [[Zaječar]] (Serbia).{{sfn|Ličnosti}}

Reko deserted from the JNA in April 1992.{{sfn|DW 2017}} While wanting to preserve "[[Brotherhood and Unity]]", the real situation, when the war spilled over into Bosnia and his home village, forced him to leave the JNA.{{sfn|B92 2017}} He had received information that Serb forces occupied Foča and his village.{{sfn|B92 2017}} He contacted his ethnic Serb friend and JNA colleague Dragan Simić stationed in [[Niš]], and told him that he was to leave to be with his family.{{sfn|B92 2017}} Simić offered to help, and the two went for Bosnia.{{sfn|B92 2017}} They crossed Serb-held territory into Bosniak-held territory in [[Goražde]] where Reko believed his family took refuge.{{sfn|DW 2017}} His colleague saved him from Bosnian Serb policemen at [[Ustiprača]].{{sfn|DW 2017}}

Reko became the first commander of the 43rd Drina Assault Brigade ({{lang|bs|43. Drinska udarna brigada}}) of ARBiH, based in Goražde.{{sfn|DW 2017}} His high rank came as the result of his Military Academy diploma.{{sfn|DW 2017}} His ''nom de guerre'' became ''Makedonac'' due to his years of service in Bitola.{{sfn|DW 2017}} He was unable to meet up with his family in Gudelj, as that village was under [[Army of Republika Srpska]] (VRS) control.{{sfn|DW 2017}} Serb soldiers killed his mother Aziza and grandfather (along with five other family members{{sfn|B92 2017}}) while [[ethnic cleansing|cleansing]] the village of the remaining people, through setting a house which held them on fire.{{sfn|DW 2017}} Reko has stated that he knows of the perpetrators, and that one lives in Canada.{{sfn|B92 2017}} A few days after, the Municipal headquarters of the Territorial Defense ordered that the Serb village of Bučje be cleansed as it posed a threat due to VRS progress.{{sfn|DW 2017}} While an ideal chance for revenge, Reko refused, and was called weak and a traitor.{{sfn|DW 2017}} He organized talks with the Bučje inhabitants for the peaceful surrender of them and their weapons.{{sfn|DW 2017}} As a result, the village's 45 Serbs and few Bosniaks were saved.{{sfn|DW 2017}} Reko learnt that he was an assassination target due to saving Serbs, and that orders came from people currently in the Bosnian government.{{sfn|B92 2017}} After the war he set up a memorial to the killed members of his family.{{sfn|DW 2017}}

After the war, he moved to [[Denmark]].{{sfn|Ličnosti}} He became a successful businessman,{{sfn|DW 2017}} and established a family, with two children.{{sfn|B92 2017}} He and his wife eventually divorced.{{sfn|B92 2017}} In 2008, he met with his childhood romance Azra in Bosnia, who was a widow with two children.{{sfn|B92 2017}} They eventually married.{{sfn|B92 2017}}

He owns a Danish-Bosnian company "Bohen" that produces gaskets, parts of rubber and plastic and parts for water and heating.{{sfn|Ličnosti}} He currently lives in Denmark with his family.{{sfn|Ličnosti}} Reko established the political movement "Most 21", aimed at a multi-ethnic unitary state.{{sfn|B92 2017}}

A documentary on his life was made in 2016, called ''Makedonac''.{{sfn|DW 2017}} There is plans of a movie.{{sfn|DW 2017}} He has been interviewed by various newspapers and guested TV shows such as [[RTRS]]'s ''Telering'',<ref>{{cite web|title=RTRS - TELERING 05.7.2017.|publisher=RTRS (via YouTube)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wDs63ZCNY2M}}</ref> [[Prva Srpska Televizija|Prva]]'s ''Život Priča'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Život priča - Čov(J)ek|publisher=PRVA (via YouTube)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QxUyzPCk4f4}}</ref> [[Face TV (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Face]]'s ''Face to Face'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Amir Reko, kapetan koji je spasio 52 Srba: "Tri dana prije ubili su sve moje, ja nisam htio..."|publisher=FACE HD TV (via YouTube)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fggXjIv5aQc}}</ref> [[Happy TV]]'s ''Jutarnji program'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Amir Reko, heroj koji je spasio 45 civila od smrti - Dobro jutro Srbijo - (TV Happy 11.12.2017)|publisher=Jutarnji Program TV HAPPY (via YouTube)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=osz2uC_ZiOw}}</ref> Elta's ''Razgovor'',<ref>{{cite web|title=RAZGOVOR AMIR REKO I DRAGAN SIMIC|publisher=Elta HD (via YouTube)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ni4J95eMJAs}}</ref> OSMTV's ''Lice Nacije''.<ref>{{cite web|title=LICE NACIJE OSMTV, gosti Amir Reko i Olivera Markovic 22 11 2017|publisher=OSM Televizija (via YouTube)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CYOVhEyhr7g}}</ref>

